  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
  <p>No model is complete. Here's what a DCF inherently misses — and how it might bias our estimate.</p>

  <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Strategic Acquisitions:</strong> Ecolab frequently bolsters growth via tuck-in acquisitions. The DCF only reflects organic cash flows.</li>
    <li><strong>Margin Expansion:</strong> If digital initiatives and pricing power push margins beyond historical norms, FCF could dramatically exceed our 8% trajectory.</li>
    <li><strong>Flight to Quality:</strong> In turbulent markets, investors willingly pay a premium (lower discount rate) for Ecolab's defensive characteristics, driving the share price above standard intrinsic value estimates.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Raw Material Inflation:</strong> Prolonged inflationary pressure on chemical inputs could squeeze margins if pricing power hits a ceiling.</li>
    <li><strong>Industrial Slowdown:</strong> While defensive, Ecolab still serves industrial, hospitality, and energy sectors that are sensitive to macroeconomic cycles.</li>
    <li><strong>Valuation Premium:</strong> The market often prices ECL at a significant premium to its DCF value due to its moat; if that sentiment shifts, the stock could revert sharply to intrinsic value.</li>
  </ul>

